{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488349"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:38:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:38:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"418"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/418"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.03,0.07,0.14,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115161"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/418"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97169"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1412"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2711"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45992"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115161"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a single episode of severe epigastric pain. The pain resolved spontaneously prior to her visit. Her medical history includes hypertension and osteoarthritis of her spine, for which she takes perindopril and paracetamol as required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals no tenderness, masses, or organomegaly. A computed tomography scan of the abdomen is performed, which shows no abnormalities to explain her epigastric pain but incidentally reveals a 1 cm solid lesion in the upper pole of the left kidney, consistent with renal cell carcinoma. The patient is counselled on the management options.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surveillance","Radiotherapy","Left nephrectomy","Fine needle aspiration cytology","Left heminephrectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents an incidentally discovered small renal mass in an elderly patient. The 1 cm solid lesion in the upper pole of the left kidney is consistent with renal cell carcinoma (RCC). The small size of the lesion and the patient\u0027s age and physical condition are important considerations for management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurveillance\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management option for this patient. Small renal masses (less than 4 cm) in elderly patients are typically slow-growing with low metastatic potential. Active surveillance involves regular imaging (ultrasound or CT) every 6-12 months to monitor for growth. It has been shown that the growth rate of these small renal masses is very slow, with only about 1% of these patients progressing to metastatic disease. This approach avoids unnecessary surgical intervention and its associated risks in an 83-year-old patient with a lesion that may never become clinically significant during her lifetime.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration cytology\u003C/strong\u003E has limited utility in the diagnostic workup of small renal masses. The procedure has a high non-diagnostic rate for small lesions and rarely changes management decisions. Additionally, if the mass is indeed RCC, the risk of needle tract seeding, though small, exists. Biopsy might be considered if the results would alter management, but in this case, surveillance would be recommended regardless.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft heminephrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E (partial nephrectomy) removes the tumor while preserving normal renal parenchyma. While this is the standard of care for small renal masses in younger patients with good health status, it still represents a significant surgical intervention with potential complications. For an 80-year-old with a 1 cm mass, the risks of surgery outweigh the potential benefits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft nephrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E (radical nephrectomy) is overly aggressive for a 1 cm renal mass. This procedure removes the entire kidney and is typically reserved for larger tumors or those in locations that make partial nephrectomy technically challenging. The risks of surgery and potential impact on renal function outweigh the benefits for this small lesion in an elderly patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard primary treatment for localised RCC as these tumours are relatively radioresistant. It may be used in palliative settings for metastatic disease or in patients who cannot tolerate other interventions, but it would not be appropriate as first-line management for this small, incidental renal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf during surveillance the lesion demonstrates significant growth (typically \u0026gt;0.5 cm per year) or reaches \u0026gt;3-4 cm, then intervention might be reconsidered. Options at that point could include partial nephrectomy or ablative therapies such as cryoablation or radiofrequency ablation, which are less invasive than surgery and may be more appropriate for elderly patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small renal cell carcinomas (\u003C4 cm) are typically slow-growing and can be managed with active surveillance in elderly patients.","Age, comorbidities, and tumour characteristics are key factors in determining management of incidental renal masses.","Regular imaging follow-up is essential for active surveillance of small renal masses."],"references":["Hsieh JJ, Purdue MP, Signoretti S, Swanton C, Albiges L, Schmidinger M, et al. Renal cell carcinoma. Nature Reviews Disease Primers. 2017;3(1):17009. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/nrdp20179#citeas","Sahni VA, Silverman SG. Imaging management of incidentally detected small renal masses. Semin Intervent Radiol. 2014 Mar;31(1):9-19. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3930647/","Gray RE, Harris GT. Renal Cell Carcinoma: Diagnosis and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Feb 1;99(3):179-184. Erratum in: Am Fam Physician. 2019 Jun 15;99(12):732. PMID: 30702258. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2019/0201/p179.html","Ljungberg B, Albiges L, Abu-Ghanem Y, et al. European Association of Urology Guidelines on Renal Cell  Carcinoma: The 2019 Update. Euro Urol 2019; 75:799-810."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97169"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"418"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97169"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T20:41:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T20:43:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"418"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115161"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","link